e life of one of the marchers, Viola Liuzzo, a Detroit mother of five. Turner offers an insider's view of the three trials that took place over the following nine months--which finally resulted in the conviction of the killers. Despite eyewitness testimony by an FBI informant who was riding in the car with the killers, two all-white state juries refused to convict. It took a team of Civil Rights Division lawyers, led by the legendary John Doar, to produce the landmark jury verdict that klansmen were no longer above the law. This is must reading today, as the voting rights won in Selma come under renewed attack.  aDescription based on information from the publisher.10aLiuzzo, Viola,d1925-1965.20aSelma to Montgomery Rights Marchd(1965 :cSelma, Ala.) 0aCivil rights movementszSouthern StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aTrials (Murder)zAlabama. 4aElectronic books.2 aMichigan Publishing (University of Michigan)epublisher.1 iSupplement (work):aTurner, James P.,tSelma and the Liuzzo murder trials.h1 online resource (Court documents, court transcripts, exhibits, and memoranda.)40zAccess to the Michigan Publishing online version:uhttps://doi.org/10.3998/mpub.9753373